TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Does Lag Structure Really Matter in Optimizing Advertising Expenditures?
AU  - Magat, Wesley A.
AU  - McCann, John M.
AU  - Morey, Richard C.
Y1  - 1986/02/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.32.2.182
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.32.2.182
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 182
EP  - 193
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A paper by Bultez and Naert in the May 1979 issue of Management Science tentatively concludes that profits are relatively insensitive to misspecification of the lag structure of advertising. We examine the conditions under which a firm's profits are most likely to be sensitive to the misspecification of the lag structure. Our analysis indicates how this sensitivity is related to (a) the form of the true lag structure, (b) the demand function, (c) the cost function, and (d) the firm's discount rate.
AB  - A paper by Bultez and Naert in the May 1979 issue of Management Science tentatively concludes that profits are relatively insensitive to misspecification of the lag structure of advertising. We examine the conditions under which a firm's profits are most likely to be sensitive to the misspecification of the lag structure. Our analysis indicates how this sensitivity is related to (a) the form of the true lag structure, (b) the demand function, (c) the cost function, and (d) the firm's discount rate.
